{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20161210182749|754072377","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Steve_Knight_(politician)","to":"Steve Knight (politician)"}],"pages":{"22768901":{"pageid":22768901,"ns":0,"title":"Steve Knight (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2016-12-23T22:48:49Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox congressman\n|birthname       =\n|name            = Steve Knight\n|image           = Steve Knight official congressional photo.jpeg\n|state           = [[California]]\n|district        = [[California's 25th congressional district|25th]]\n|term_start      = January 3, 2015\n|term_end        = \n|preceded        = [[Buck McKeon]]\n|succeeded       = \n|state_senate2   = California State\n|district2       = [[California's 21st Senate district|21st]]\n|term_start2     = December 3, 2012\n|term_end2       = January 3, 2015\n|predecessor2    = [[Sharon Runner]] ''(redistricted)''\n|successor2      = [[Sharon Runner]]\n|state_assembly3 = California\n|district3       = [[California's 36th State Assembly district|36th]]\n|term_start3     = December 1, 2008\n|term_end3       = November 30, 2012\n|predecessor3    = [[Sharon Runner]]\n|successor3      = [[Steve Fox (politician)|Steve Fox]]\n|office4         = [[Palmdale, California|Palmdale]] City Councilman\n|term_start4     = December 5, 2005\n|term_end4       = December 1, 2008\n|predecessor4    = \n|successor4      = Laura Bettencourt\n|birth_name      = Stephen Thomas Knight\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1966|12|17}}\n|birth_place     = [[Edwards Air Force Base]], [[Antelope Valley, California]], U.S.\n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|nationality     = [[United States|American]]\n|party           = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse          = Lily Knight\n|residence       = [[Palmdale, California]], U.S.\n|alma_mater      = [[Antelope Valley College]]\n|profession      = Police officer\n|religion        = [[Roman Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2014-new-members/california-25-steve-knight-r-20141105|title=California-25: Steve Knight (R)|work=www.nationaljournal.com|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref>\n|website         = {{Official website|http://knight.house.gov}}\n|allegiance      = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch          = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears=1985-1993\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Thomas \"Steve\" Knight''' (born December 17, 1966) is an [[United States|American]] politician. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[California's 25th congressional district]]. Previously, he represented [[California's 21st State Senate district]] from 2012\u201314 and [[California's 36th State Assembly district]] from 2008 through 2012. From 2010-12, he served as Assistant Minority Leader in the California State Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Perry|title=Speculation Begins For Steve Knight\u2019s State Senate Seat|url=http://www.hometownstation.com/santa-clarita-latest-news/speculation-begins-for-steve-knights-state-senate-seat-93233|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=KHTS|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nKnight served in the U.S. Army from 1985 to 1993 and served for 18 years with the [[Los Angeles Police Department]]. He was previously a member of the [[Palmdale, California]] City Council.\n\n==Early life, military service and career==\nKnight was born at [[Edwards Air Force Base]] in the Antelope Valley on December 17, 1966.<ref>{{cite web|title=KNIGHT, Steve, (1966 - )|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=K000387|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref> After graduating from [[Palmdale High School]], he served in the U.S. Army from 1985-87 as a track systems mechanic in [[Friedberg, Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|title=New Members Guide 2015|url=http://thehill.com/new-members-guide-2014/223672-rep-elect-steve-knight-r-calif-25|accessdate=17 February 2016|publisher=The Hill}}</ref> When his tour ended, he served in the Army Reserve, and his total military service spanned from 1985 to 1993.<ref>{{cite news|date=December 1, 2014 |title=New Members of the 114th Congress Who Have Served in the Military|url=http://www.ebmpubs.com/ECN_pdfs/ecn1214_News.pdf|newspaper=Exchange and Commissary News|publisher=Executive Business Media|location=Westbury, NY|page=11}}</ref> In 2006, Knight received an [[Associate degree|associate of arts]] degree from [[Antelope Valley College]].<ref name=rollcall>{{cite web|url=http://media.cq.com/members/53674?rc=1|title=House of Representatives Member Profile; Rep. Steve Knight|date=September 8, 2014|website=RollCall.com|publisher=CQ-Roll Call, Inc.|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\nKnight served for 18 years with the [[Los Angeles Police Department]], where he was selected to serve on the [[Community Resources Against Street Hoodlums]] (CRASH) team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Knight (R) - District 21|url=http://archive.senate.ca.gov/content/steve-knight-r-district-21|publisher=California State Senate|accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref> He served on the [[Palmdale, California|Palmdale City Council]] and represented the north Los Angeles County area in both the [[California State Assembly]] and [[California State Senate]].<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|last1=Panzar|first1=Javier|title=Democratic lawyer announcing challenge to GOP Rep. Steve Knight|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-bryan-caforio-steve-knight-20151210-story.html|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=December 10, 2015}}</ref> [[File:Steve Knight - LA County Sheriff Dept.jpg|thumb|Steve Knight speaks with members of the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]]\n\n==California State Legislature==\nKnight was elected to the California State Assembly in November 2008, succeeding [[Sharon Runner]]. From 2010 to 2012, he was the Assistant Minority Leader of the California State Assembly.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Knight's Biography|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/71098/steve-knight#.VsTXFvHvOac|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> In 2012, Knight was elected to the California State Senate, where he represented the 21st District until 2014. His father, the late [[William J. Knight|William J. \"Pete\" Knight]] served as Republican state senator in the Antelope Valley.<ref name=latimes/>\n\nIn the State Assembly, Knight was vice chairman of the natural resources and public safety committees and served on the aerospace; local government; utilities and commerce; and Rules Committees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Our View: Knight for state Senate|url=http://www.signalscv.com/m/archives/77155/|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Santa Clarita Valley Signal|date=October 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Knight was one of three legislators who voted against a measure barring the display or sale of [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Confederate flag]] images from California state museums and gift shops.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merl|first1=Jean|title=Confederate flag vote puts Knight on spot in congressional race|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/political/la-me-pc-steve-knight-flag-20140827-story.html|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=August 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile in the [[California State Legislature]], Knight focused his efforts on reducing the tax burden on California families and businesses, and restoring the state's economic vitality during the [[Great Recession in the Americas|Great Recession]]. In September 2014, California Governor [[Jerry Brown]] signed a bill introduced by Knight that aimed to protect California\u2019s disabled veterans by fixing an issue with property tax exemptions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gov. Brown passes bill for disabled veterans|url=http://www.vvdailypress.com/article/20140930/NEWS/140939994|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Daily Press|date=September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Knight Measures To Help Veterans, And Protect The Disabled Clear The Senate|url=http://highdesertdaily.com/2014/05/knight-measures-veterans-protect-disabled-clear-senate|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=High Desert Daily|date=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2014 election===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2014#District 25}}\n\nKnight focused his 2014 campaign on jobs and education.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Simon|first1=Melissa|title=Strickland, Knight focus on jobs, education|url=http://www.simivalleyacorn.com/news/2014-10-24/Community/Strickland_Knight_focus_on_jobs_education.html|accessdate=17 February 2016|publisher=Simi Valley Acorn|date=October 24, 2014}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' endorsed Knight in the 2014 primary election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Endorsement: Steve Knight for Congress in California's 25th District|url=http://www.dailynews.com/opinion/20140508/endorsement-steve-knight-for-congress-in-californias-25th-district|accessdate=17 February 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|date=May 8, 2014}}</ref> Due to California's blanket primary system, Knight faced fellow Republican [[Tony Strickland]] in the November 4, 2014, general election. Knight defeated Strickland with 53% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winburn|first1=Jim|title=2014 General Election results of interest to Antelope Valley voters|url=http://theavtimes.com/2014/11/05/2014-general-election-results-of-interest-to-antelope-valley-voters/|accessdate=17 February 2016|publisher=The Antelope Valley Times|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2016 election===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2016#District 25}}\nIn May 2015, the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] named Knight to its Patriot Program. The program gives added attention by the party to reelection campaigns in districts most likely to switch to Democratic representation in upcoming elections.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merl|first1=Jean|title=Republicans add Californians to list of its vulnerable House members|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/political/la-me-pc-knight-denham-20150501-story.html|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=May 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Knight participated in a public debate with his Democratic challengers. In it he said that immigration reform should focus on those who want to move to the U.S. legally. In a debate with other candidates, Knight called Social Security \"a bad idea\" and warned that the U.S. Social Security system retirement system will run out of money by 2030 if major changes are not implemented.<ref>[http://www.signalscv.com/section/36/article/151806 Candid debate at Hart Hall], ''Santa Clarita Valley Signal'', May 5, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, analyst David Wasserman moved Knight's district into the \"toss-up\" category, due to the negative influence of Republican presidential nominee Donald Trump on down-ticket races and the growth in Democratic voter registration in the 25th Congressional District.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-sac-essential-politics-is-rep-steve-knight-california-s-most-1465608040-htmlstory.html \"Is Rep. Steve Knight California's most endangered incumbent?\"], ''L.A. Times'', June 30, 2016.</ref> In addition to Knight, two Democrats and one other Republican filed to run in the district's [[Nonpartisan blanket primary|top-two primary]], which took place on June 7, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wenner|first1=Gretchen|title=Knight faces three primary challengers in 25th congressional district|url=http://www.vcstar.com/news/local/simi-valley/knight-faces-three-primary-challengers-in-25th-congressional-district-30de50c3-4f47-74fd-e053-010000-377049401.html|accessdate=29 April 2016|publisher=Ventura County Star|date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Knight and Democrat Bryan Caforio advanced to the general election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Daly|first1=Krista|title=It's Knight, Caforio in November election for 25th Congressional District|url=http://www.signalscv.com/section/36/article/153095|accessdate=June 8, 2016|publisher=Santa Clarita Valley Signal|date=June 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKnight was endorsed by the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Re-elect Steve Knight to Congress in 25th District: Endorsement|url=http://www.dailynews.com/opinion/20160930/re-elect-steve-knight-to-congress-in-25th-district-endorsement|accessdate=October 6, 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|date=September 30, 2016}}</ref> He was also endorsed by Lou Vince, an L.A. police lieutenant and Democrat who finished third (behind Knight and Bryan Caforio) in the 25th district's June 2016 primary.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Panzar|first1=Javier|title=Democrat who lost in the primary says he will vote for Republican Rep. Steve Knight in heated House race|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-sac-essential-politics-updates-democrat-who-lost-in-the-primary-says-1475190691-htmlstory.html|accessdate=October 6, 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=September 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKnight did not make an endorsement in the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 U.S. presidential election]], saying that he could not support Democratic nominee [[Hillary Clinton]] or Republican nominee [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Samuels|first1=Nikolas|title=Congressman Steve Knight releases statement on Saturday saying he \u2018cannot support\u2019 Donald Trump|url=http://www.signalscv.com/2016/10/08/steve-knight-releases-statement-saying-cannot-support-donald-trump|accessdate=October 20, 2016|publisher=Santa Clarita Valley Signal|date=October 8, 2016}}</ref> Knight said he was \"deeply disturbed\" by reports that in 2005 Trump bragged about grabbing and groping women without their consent.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-sac-essential-politics-updates-did-knight-say-he-ll-vote-for-donald-1476471534-htmlstory.html \"Did Knight Say He'll Vote for Donald?\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', October 14, 2016.</ref>\n\nKnight was re-elected in the general election on November 8, 2016. He defeated Democrat Bryan Caforio with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Bartholomew|title=Brownley, Knight, Carbajal win House seats|url=http://www.vcstar.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/11/09/brownley-knight-carbajal-win-house-seats/93553618/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|agency=USA Today|publisher=Ventura County Star|date=November 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nKnight was sworn into office on January 6, 2015, aged 48.<ref>{{cite news|title=Congressman Steve Knight Sworn Into Office|url=http://www.hometownstation.com/santa-clarita-news/congressman-steve-knight-sworn-into-office-117993|accessdate=17 February 2016|publisher=KHTS|date=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Knight had a verbal altercation with a protester. After the protester touched him, Knight threatened him but later apologized.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bump|first1=Philip|title=California Rep. Steve Knight tells a protester, \"I\u2019ll drop your ass\"|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/04/21/california-rep-steve-knight-tells-a-protestor-ill-drop-your-ass|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Washington Post|date=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Knight voted to impose a one-year delay on new Department of Defense rules designed to shield military families from abusive terms on payday loans and other forms of expensive short-term credit.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/04/30/payday-lending-soldiers_n_7182510.html \"Democrats Defeat GOP Plan to Block Predatory Lending Protections For Soldiers\"], ''The Huffington Post'', April 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nKnight has authored a bill that would create a national memorial to mark the site of the [[St. Francis Dam]] disaster in the Santa Clarita Valley.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Money|first1=Luke|title=Knight cites frustrations, progress during first year in Congress|url=http://www.signalscv.com/section/36/article/146812/|accessdate=17 February 2016|publisher=Santa Clarita Valley Signal|date=January 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the [[Aliso Canyon gas leak]], which became public in October 2015, Knight was criticized by some residents in his district for his reaction to the leak. He did not visit the [[Porter Ranch]] gas leak site until January 8, 2016, saying that he did not want to politicize the problem.<ref>\"As Porter Ranch Gas Leak Lingers, Candidates Smell a Political Opportunity\" Los Angeles Times, January 18, 2016.</ref> The ''[[New York Times]]'' reported that Knight, who has received campaign donations from Sempra Energy, said in December 2015 that he was confident that SoCalGas was \u201cworking on this as diligently as they can.\u201d<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/03/magazine/the-invisible-catastrophe.html \"The Invisible Catastrophe\"], ''New York Times'', March 31, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Knight introduced a bill that would block mining at [[Soledad Canyon]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Money|first1=Luke|title=Wilk introduces \u2018Plan B\u2019 to help block Cemex mine|url=http://www.signalscv.com/section/36/article/148699|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Santa Clarita Valley Signal|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref> Knight also introduced legislation intended to increase federal regulation of gas storage facilities and prevent natural gas leaks.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Patrick|title=Energy Secretary Calls for 'Fresh Look' at Regulation After Gas Leak|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Energy-Secretary-Calls-for-Fresh-Look-at-Regulation-After-Gas-Leak-369068501.html|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=NBC|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref> Knight's legislation was merged into a bipartisan bill named the Protecting our Infrastructure of Pipelines and Enhancing Safety Act of 2016. In April 2016, the bill was passed unanimously by the [[House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bartholomew|first1=Dana|title=Valley lawmakers continue push for safer natural gas storage|url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20160424/valley-lawmakers-continue-push-for-safer-natural-gas-storage|accessdate=April 29, 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> In June 2016, Knight's bill was signed into law by President Obama.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bartholomew|first1=Dana|title=National bill signed to prevent gas leaks like the one near Porter Ranch|url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20160622/national-bill-signed-to-prevent-gas-leaks-like-the-one-near-porter-ranch|accessdate=28 June 2016|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|date=June 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlso in February 2016, Knight introduced legislation that would allow the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] to continue and expand upon its research, engineering and development programs through 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Varela|first1=Rob|title=Knight pushes FAA bill to expand aerospace research|url=http://www.vcstar.com/news/local/simi-valley/knight-pushes-faa-bill-to-expand-aerospace-research--2b4b40f2-ff18-6b5f-e053-0100007f00ba-368099581.html|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=Ventura County Star|date=February 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Knight Introduces Aerospace Research Legislation|url=http://www.hometownstation.com/santa-clarita-news/press-releases/knight-introduces-aerospace-research-legislation-166924|accessdate=February 17, 2016|publisher=KHTS|date=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Subcommittee on Military Personnel]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Energy|Subcommittee on Energy]] (Vice Chair)\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Contracting and Workforce|Subcommittee on Contracting and Workforce]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations|Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations]]\n\n==Personal life==\nKnight is [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]; he lives in [[Palmdale, California|Palmdale]] with his wife Lily and their two sons.<ref name=rollcall/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://knight.house.gov}}\n* [http://steveknight.org/ Campaign website]\n* {{ballotpedia|Stephen_Knight|Stephen Knight}}\n* [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/steve_knight/412614 Steve Knight at GovTrack]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=California|\n  district=25 |\n  before=[[Buck McKeon]] |\n  start=January 3, 2015\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John 